    Sunder me from my bones, O sword of God,
    Till they stand stark and strange as do the trees;
    That I whose heart goes up with the soaring

    I dreamed a dream of heaven, white as frost,
    The splendid stillness of a living host;
    Vast choirs of upturned faces, line o'er line.

    Were I that wandering citizen whose city is the world,
    I would not weep for all that fell before the flags were furled;
    I would not let

    Blessings there are of cradle and of clan,
    Blessings that fall of priests' and princes' hands;
    But never blessing full of lives and land

    The silver and violet leopard of the night
    Spotted with stars and smooth with silence sprang;
    And though three doors stood open, the end

    Trampled yet red is the last of the embers,
    Red the last cloud of a sun that has set;
    What of your sleeping though Flanders remembers,

    I had grown weary of him; of his breath
    And hands and features I was sick to death.
    Each day I heard the same dull voice and tread;

    Stilton, thou shouldst be living at this hour
    And so thou art. Nor losest grace thereby;
    England has need of thee, and so have I--
